    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-04-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-04-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="316"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d316">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72/2634½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to President
                            <persName type="to">Wilson</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-04-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 24, 1916</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. President</hi>: I enclose a memorandum on the
                        <hi rend="italic">status</hi> of armed merchant vessels, which I prepared a
                    month ago.<note n="45" xml:id="d316fn1">For text of this memorandum as made
                        public on April 27, see <ref target="frus1916Supp#pg_244">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p. 244</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0420" n="352" xml:id="pg_352"/>
                <p>It is possible that Germany may abandon submarine war against merchant vessels,
                    and then attack vessels with armaments, claiming that they are not merchant
                    vessels. I think that we should be prepared to meet this move at the very
                    outset, otherwise they will appeal to the letter of January 18th<note n="46"
                        xml:id="d316fn2">
                        <ref target="frus1916Supp#pg_146">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1916, supp., p.
                        146</ref>.</note> as an expression of the ideas of this Government.</p>
                <p>The memorandum was prepared to show the consistency of the statements in the
                    letter of January 18th with the accepted rules as to the arming of merchant
                    vessels.</p>
                <p>I would be obliged if you could let me know at Cabinet tomorrow whether you
                    approve of the memorandum as I may have to use the substance orally in
                    interviews with Count Bernstorff.</p>
                <p>Faithfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
